S-s-h keys, the right way to authenticate.

Password authentication works, but it has two real problems: passwords can be guessed, and you have to type one every single time. S-s-h keys solve both. A key is a cryptographic pair of two parts. The private key stays on your own machine and is never shared with anyone. The public key is copied onto every server you want to reach. When you connect, the server issues a challenge that only the holder of the matching private key can answer, so no password ever crosses the wire, and you are not prompted for one.

To create a key you run s-s-h-keygen, choosing the modern recommended algorithm, e-d twenty-five-five-one-nine, which is fast, secure, and produces small keys. It asks where to save the files, defaulting to a sensible place in your s-s-h directory, and it asks for a passphrase. Always set a passphrase on a real machine; it encrypts the private key on disk, and as we will see, the agent means you only type it once per session. Afterward you have two files: the private key, which you must never share and which must be readable only by you, and the public key, ending in dot pub, which is perfectly safe to hand out.

The easiest way to install your public key on a server is the s-s-h-copy-id command, which appends it to the authorized-keys file on the server, creating that file with the correct permissions if needed. After that, logging in should no longer ask for a password. If that helper is unavailable, you can do the same thing by hand, piping the public key over an ordinary s-s-h connection. One last point that trips many people: s-s-h is deliberately strict about permissions and will refuse to use your keys if they are too open. Your s-s-h directory should be accessible only by you, and your private key and the authorized-keys file must be readable and writable only by you. Get those permissions wrong and key authentication silently fails.
